 HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nukepulse>NukePulse</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 33<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/2/02 2:04:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=207.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Nuclear Thermal Linear or toroidal  Spike Engine</span><hr size=1> I wonder if it would be possible to apply the greater efficiency of a Linear or toroidal spike nozzle configuration to a NTR? <br>
<br>
It doesn’t seem to be in the cards for an Orion or GCNR program to start up anytime soon so perhaps we should discuss ways of maximizing the capabilities of NTR's.<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nukepulse>NukePulse</A> at: 12/2/02 2:07:30 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 136<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/2/02 2:12:04 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=207.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Nuclear Thermal Linear or toroidal  Spike Engine</span><hr size=1> I think so.  In my obsessive work on the GCNR powered SSTO, I have settled on a plug nozzle design for the thrusters.  <br>
<br>
For a crude drawing of what I am thinking of, see <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.angelfire.com/space/nuclearmauk2/"> www.angelfire.com/space/nuclearmauk2/ </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Click on the lowest link for a giant picture, with notes.  <br>
<br>
I think the same sort of a setup could be used for many types of NTR.  Instead of dumping the exhaust into a nozzle, dump it into a plenum and exhaust it around the edges, using the bottom of the plenum as your toroidal Spike engine. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A> at: 12/2/02 2:14:23 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 505<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/2/02 2:46:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=207.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Nuclear Thermal Linear or toroidal  Spike Engine</span><hr size=1> Everytime I see that diagram the more I love it.  I think the idea of a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>reusable</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> rocket that could lift 1000 tons into orbit would blow the minds of most people at NASA, or most other places for that matter.    <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nukepulse>NukePulse</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 34<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/2/02 3:26:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=207.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Hey mauk2</span><hr size=1> Mauk2 <br>
