 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nukepulse>NukePulse</A> at: 12/2/02 5:04:44 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=discovery1@nuclearspace>Discovery 1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 189<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/2/02 9:00:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=207.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Nuclear Thermal Linear or toroidal  Spike Engine</span><hr size=1> NukePulse or Mauk2, I'm very thick, so may I ask why an aerospike nozzle offers superior performance than parabolic nozzle? Also could you give relatively quick version of how an aerospike nozzle works? I would appreciate it. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=discovery1@nuclearspace>Discovery 1</A> at: 12/2/02 9:03:30 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 139<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/3/02 12:17:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=207.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Nuclear Thermal Linear or toroidal  Spike Engine</span><hr size=1> Discovery1: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> NukePulse or Mauk2, I'm very thick, so may I ask why an aerospike nozzle offers superior performance than parabolic nozzle? Also could you give relatively quick version of how an aerospike nozzle works? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Boy, you have a positive talent for asking tough ones.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Okay, uhm, first lets discuss a classic &quot;bell&quot; nozzle.  <br>
<br>
The object of a rocket nozzle is to extract the maximum amount of energy from the gas stream in the form of thrust.  It does this by allowing the hot, dense gases from the combustion chamber to expand inside it, which has the handy side effect of causing the gas stream to blast out of the huge open mouth of the nozzle at high speeds.<br>
<br>
Pretty simple stuff, and a conventional nozzle can be very efficient.  The problem arises when you have external gas pressure.  (The atmosphere.)<br>
<br>
To understand this phenomenon, let's do a little thoought experiment.<br>
<br>
Suppose we have a rocket nozzle.  The little opening at the top, the throat, is where the hot, dense gas comes in.  The huge opening at the other end is where the gases leave at high speed, after expanding as far as possible inside the nozzle.  Now, imagine that the throat is one square foot in area, while the big opening where the exhaust leaves is one hundred square feet in area.<br>
<br>
The gas has to expand 100 times to get from the throat to the exit, while still &quot;filling up&quot; the entire nozzle.  Suppose then, that the gas as it enters the rocket nozzle is at 1000 pounds per square inch in pressure.  It is easy to see  that as the gas leaves, having expanded 100 times, it is now at a pressure of ten pounds per square inch(psi).<br>
<br>
Now, what happens if you fire this motor, using this nozzle, at sea level, where the air pressure is 15 psi?  Well, obviously, the exiting rocket exhaust will not be able to fill up the entire nozzle!  The gas flow will seperate from the nozzle wall up inside the nozzle, where the pressure matches the external pressure.<br>
<br>
This is BAD.  This causes vibration, shockwaves, uneven heating inside the nozzle, its just BAD.  <br>
<br>
So, to fix this, we shrink the bell nozzle until the large exit opening is only 60 square feet in size, but we leaave the throat at one square foot.  Now, the exhaust gases leave the nozzle at a pressure of 16.67 psi, and all is well.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately, as you start flying up towards orbit, the outside pressure starts dropping, and soon the external pressure is at zero.  Now, your 60 to 1 nozzle is inefficient!  If it was bigger, it would be squeezing more power out of the exhaust.  As it is, the exhaust now &quot;blooms&quot; out in a huge fat plume, with a lot of energy being wasted in making the exhaust plume fatter rather than faster.<br>
<br>
The next time you watch a Space Shuttle launch, watch carefully the exhaust plumes of the SSME's vs the big solids.  At ground level, the SSME's are blasting these little narrow pencils of blue exhaust gases,  while the solids have nice, straight plumes.  The nozzles on the SSME's have a much higher expansion ratio than the SSRB's do:  The solids are optimized for low altitudes, while the SSME's are optimized for high altitudes.<br>
<br>
Conversely, when the solids burn out, look carefully at the plumes of the solids right before they are jettisoned.  Notice how the plumes are huge and fat now, full of wasted energy.  Meanwhile, the SSME plumes are now nicely shaped, getting maximum Isp from their fuel.<br>
<br>
You may ask yourself,  &quot;How can just air make such a difference?&quot;  Well, think of it this way.  If the exit plane of your nozzle is one hundred square feet, that is 14,400 square inches.  If you have to push your exhaust gases into a thick soupy atmosphere at 15 psi, versus a nice crisp vacuum, you have to push your exhaust gases out against a total force of 216,000 pounds!!!  <br>
<br>
Ok, all of that is concerning standard nozzles.  <br>
<br>
Well, if you can build a rocket with stages, it is easy to simply put standard nozzles of different expansion ratios on each stage, start with smaller ratios and go to larger ones as you go higher.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately, in the interest of simplicity, with the power afforded by nuclear, we want to take the same stage all the way up.<br>
<br>
Fortunately for us, smart people decades ago figured out a way to do this with one nozzle.  <br>
<br>
A &quot;plug&quot; nozzle, or an &quot;aerospike&quot; nozzle, is basically a bell nozzle turned &quot;inside out.&quot;  Instead of a small round throat hole to inject the hot gases inside a bell, there is a large narrow round slit to eject the hot gases in a large circle, squirting inwards at a single slender spike.  As the hot gas squirts inwards, it expands out into the open space, producing just as much thrust as a bell nozzle would.  <br>
<br>
As plug nozzle, or aerospike, is a weird looking and counterintuitive thing, but they have been extensively tested and they work GREAT.<br>
<br>
They are automatically pressure compensated, as the outside pressure falls, they simply expand more vigorously, since they are open to ambient along their entire length.  They are also much smaller and lighter than a bell nozzle.<br>
<br>
The only downsides are they are a little harder to keep cool, since they are small, and they have not been used much, so folks are slow to accept them.<br>
<br>
