<br>
All parabolic (Bell) shaped nozzles are designed for a specific atmospheric pressure the shapes of these nozzles are a compromise. For instance A nozzle on a first stage engine is long with respect to the area of its mouth so that it can generate a tight exhaust plume which is what you need when you are in a heavy atmosphere. Upper stage engines on the other hand have wider mouths with respect to their length and this optimizes the exhaust plumes shape in a vaccume. With a bell shaped nozzle any pressure other than the one it was designed for negatively effects the efficiency of the transportation of gas out of the nozzle. <br>
<br>
An aerospike engine avoids this loss of power by allowing the rockets exhaust plume to adjust its geometry instantly in accordance with the current atmospheric pressure. Aerospike engines have good efficiency at all altitudes. <br>
<br>
The aerospike engines ability to adjust to changing atmospheric pressure is made possible because the atmosphere itself becomes the outer wall of the nozzle. There is no mechanical adjustment of the exhaust plume as there is in a jet engine; the plume simply adjusts itself into an optimum shape in instantaneous response to the current altitude and pressure.<br>
