4: The crew space is missing in your drawing!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   At the top of the Liberty Ship is a five meter tall, 20 meter diameter space devoted to the crew.  I envision two airlocks, two docking ports for simple escape capsules, and some windows.  Maybe a lot of windows.  The Liberty Ship has the power to splurge on HUGE crew accomodations, and I suspect it will have a &quot;crew&quot; of 20 or so.  You can see the crew space in the diagram at my site, as well.  <br>
<br>
5:  Yes, I realize that with these modifications, it looks like a beer can with rocket motors.  Sorry, it just isn't built to be lovely.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
6:  Last, but not least, get that NASA logo off there!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Put nuclearspace on it you have to have a logo.  <br>
<br>
<br>
Ok, your question.:  <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Question: shouldn't the landing gear retract? to put struts anywhere near those engines might be a problem. retractable landing gear once deployed could also serve as a drag cone that would make its nose down attitude into the atmosphere more stable. Articulated landing gear could also provide a form of redundant attitude control if they each had 3 deployment positions retracted, half, and full. that kind of control would also make bringing the nose up to a stall position easier for the final leg of the descent with engines blazing.  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
As I mentioned before, the landing gear is only deployed RIGHT before landing, because I don't want to melt them.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    The twelve reaction control systems should be easily able to handle attitude control, combined with the swiveling thrusters and the possibility of using body lift as a control mechanism if all else fails.  So, no fancy tricks needed.  KISS is my motto!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
